On Tuesday, she testified that she 
Gosnell taught her to snip the babies' necks, a practice she carried out
 once when he was away from the clinic.

She
 said she took a baby that had been delivered in a toilet in the second 
trimester - between 12 and 24 weeks of pregnancy - and saw its arm move before she snipped its spine, The Delaware News Journal reported.

'I only do what I’m told to do,' she told the jury. 'What I was told to do was snip their neck.'

When
 Gosnell returned, she told him about how the newborn moved and he said 
it was simply an 'involuntary response', insisting the baby was already 
dead because of drugs the mother had taken.

She
 said it was the only time she snipped a spine because it gave her 'the 
creeps' and she insisted she did not know it was murder.

