She added it was one of her duties to pick up babies that women would spontaneously give birth to in the waiting room after getting large doses of drugs, the Philadelphia Inquirer reported.

Like many of Gosnell's employees, Williams was desperate for work when he gave her a job.

She had a poor education and had not even finished eighth grade, although went on to work as an instrument sterilizer. During this job, she met Gosnell who performed abortions at the clinic.

But
 her life began spiralling out of control when her husband was murdered 
in 2008 and she was diagnosed with bipolar and depression. She asked 
Gosnell if he had any work for her.

He hired her to sterilize instrument and soon asked her to carry out ultrasounds, administering intravenous medication and anesthesia to patients.

